{{NCAATeamSeason |Mode=Basketball |Year=1967â68 |Team=Houston Cougars |Image=University of Houston classic logo.png |ImageSize=100px |Conference=Independent |Division= |ShortConference= |CoachRank=1 |APRank=1 |Record= 31â2 |ConfRecord= |HeadCoach=[[Guy Lewis]] |AsstCoach1= Harvey Pate |AsstCoach2= |AsstCoach3= |StadiumArena=[[Delmar Fieldhouse]] |Champion= |BowlTourney=[[1968 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Men's Division I Tournament]] |BowlTourneyResult=Fourth place |Prev year=1966â67 |Next year=1968â69 }} The '''1967â68 Houston Cougars men's basketball team''' represented the [[University of Houston]] in the 1967â68 NCAA University Division men's basketball season. The team played its home games at [[Delmar Fieldhouse]] in [[Houston]] for the second consecutive season. This season marked the team's ninth year as an [[NCAA Division I independent schools (basketball)|independent]] member of the NCAA's University Division. Houston was led by twelfth-year head coach [[Guy Lewis]].
During the regular season, the [[Elvin Hayes]]-fronted Cougars team would beat the [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar|Lew Alcindor]]-led [[1967â68 UCLA Bruins men's basketball team|UCLA Bruins]] on January 20, 1968, in what was known as the [[Game of the Century (college basketball)|Game of the Century]]. Houston obtained a perfect 28â0 record for regular season play, and eventually finished with a 31â2 overall record. It was the first time in the program's history that at least 30 wins were achieved. The team finished as number one in both the [[AP Poll]] and the [[Coaches' Poll]]. The team was invited to the [[1968 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1968 NCAA Men's University Division Basketball Tournament]], and finished as a semifinalist. It was the second [[Final four|Final Four]] appearance in Houston's history.
Following the season, Elvin Hayes was drafted into the [[National Basketball Association]] by the [[Houston Rockets|San Diego Rockets]] as the [[List of first overall NBA draft picks|first overall draft pick]] in the [[1968 NBA Draft]]. [[Don Chaney]] was also taken as the twelfth overall draft pick by the [[Boston Celtics]].
